name: OpenAgreements Employee Restrictive Covenant (New Jersey)
category: non-compete
description: >-
  New Jersey-specific employee restrictive covenant agreement built for New
  Jersey's common-law reasonableness regime: there is no general New Jersey
  non-compete statute for the ordinary workforce, so every post-employment
  restraint stands or falls on the three-part Solari/Whitmyer test (protects the
  employer's legitimate interests, imposes no undue hardship on the employee, and
  is not injurious to the public). It provides confidentiality and trade-secret
  protection backstopped by the New Jersey Trade Secrets Act (N.J.S.A. 56:15-1 et
  seq.), a continued-employment consideration recital (Hogan v. Bergen Brunswig
  Corp.), customer and employee non-solicitation, an optional non-compete tied to
  identified legitimate interests and sized to the actual footprint, a
  breach-tied tolling clause (ADP, LLC v. Kusins; Community Hospital Group, Inc.
  v. More), physician public-interest scrutiny (Community Hospital Group, Inc. v.
  More; Pierson v. Medical Health Centers, P.A.), and partial enforcement that
  works with the grain of the doctrine (Solari Industries, Inc. v. Malady; ADP,
  LLC v. Rafferty). It carves out the discrimination-claim concealment bar
  (N.J.S.A. 10:5-12.8; Savage v. Township of Neptune) and disclaims practice
  restrictions for lawyers (RPC 5.6; Jacob v. Norris, McLaughlin & Marcus) and
  client-access restrictions for psychologists (N.J.A.C. 13:42-10.16;
  Comprehensive Psychology Sys., P.C. v. Prince). Drafted as a starting point for
  licensed counsel review.
